<div class="story">
	

		<p>The evolution of OBX vacations started on the shores of Nags Head. From the wealthy planters of yore to today's happy vacationers, Nags Head was and is a destination. You have probably found this page because you are considering purchasing a beach house in Nags Head. This is your lucky day, because on this page you can find every home, condo, and piece of land that is for sale in Nags Head. </p>
		<p>
			Nags Head is the southern most town on the Outer Banks, north of  Oregon Inlet. Bordered by The Atlantic Ocean on the east and the Roanoke Sound on the west and the town of <a href="https://www.outerbankshome.com/outer banks/real estate/KillDevilHills/" title="Kill Devil Hills">Kill Devil Hills</a> to the north and <a href="http://www.nps.gov/caha/index.htm" title="Cape Hatteras National Seashore" target="_blank">Cape Hatteras National Seashore</a> as the southern neighbor. 3/4 of Nags Head borders are on Nature consisting of either the Atlantic Ocean. the Roanoke Sound or Cape Hatteras National Seashore. The town is comprised of roughly 60 subdivisions/communities containing a combined total of 6400 parcels of which 1,000+- are still vacant (as of 2-1-16). The US Census Bureau indicates a year round population of 2,800 residents, underscoring the popularity of  2nd home ownership with out of sate owners.
		</p>
		<p>
			Nags Head  has 20 public ocean access areas  and 4 public sound access areas, all with free parking, including the sound beach at <a href="http://jockeysridgestatepark.com/" title="Jockeys Ridge State Park" target="_blank">Jockeys Ridge State Park</a>.  The oceanfront beach is open to the public and you can walk from one end of town to the other along the ocean's edge and never cross private property.
		</p>
